	   <tr><td colspan=2>Excellent work here. Very detailed and well explained! I will try to do the same here...<br><br>There seems to be some confustion over grouping and lvl/class/race splits. I think the original post is correct in stating that individual experience gain is proportional based on total group experience. The following numbers are purely made up (not accurate for race/level etc.) But I hope they might show how experience splitting will "appear" to be based on class and level.<br><br>Example one (the easy one):<br><br>member 1 - lvl 10 human warrior xp=1000<br>member 2 - lvl 10 human warrior xp=1000<br><br>total group xp = 2000<br>member 1 ratio is 1/2<br>member 2 ratio is 1/2<br><br>Thus, each member gets 1/2 of the xp. Assuming that these two always play together, their bubbles will fill at exactly the same rate and they will lvl on exactly the same kill.<br><br>Example two (lvl difference):<br><br>member 1 - lvl 10 human warrior xp = 1000<br>member 2 - lvl 12 human warrior xp = 1500<br><br>total group xp = 2500<br>member 1 ratio = 2/5<br>member 2 ratio = 3/5<br><br>Thus, member 2 will receive more experience than member 1. (3 xp points out of every 5) This is due to experience AND level difference - they are the same thing. The amount of experience you have determines what level you are! Without the actual numbers, I do not know if both party members will get the same "bubbles" of experience here, but I would guess they do. Member 1 will need less experience to get to the next level than member 2 will. So the bubbles may actually move at the same rate even though the "numeric" experience amounts differ.<br><br>Example three (class difference):<br><br>member 1 - lvl 10 human warrior xp = 1000<br>member 2 - lvl 10 human paladin xp = 1200<br><br>total group xp = 2200<br>member 1 ratio = 5/11<br>member 2 ratio = 6/11<br><br>Thus, member 2 will receive more experience than member 1. (6 xp points out of every 11) This is due to experience AND class difference - they are the same thing. The amount of experience you have determines what level you are! And your class helps determines how much experience you need per level. A lvl 10 paladin will have more actuall experience points than a lvl 10 warrior. Without the actual numbers, I do not know if both party members will get the same "bubbles" of experience here, but I would guess they do. Member 1 will need less experience to get to the next level than member 2 will. So the bubbles may actually move at the same rate even though the "numeric" experience amounts differ.<br><br>Conclusion:<br><br>The arguments about hybrids, classes, and levels affecting group experience sharing are all moot. I believe that all parties here are really talking about the same thing, just using different words.<br><br>Disclaimer:<br><br>All points made by me are based on my own recollections of what I have read in the past year on various boards. I have not actually perfomed any tests, but I have played for way too many hours! The above information may be all wrong and I am not liable for any personal hardship incurred as a result of their use :)<br><br>Vinitis<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
